Only in 2011 and in France, the National Commission for Information and Freedoms authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the form of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, cantines...
"Everyone will soon be identified, anywhere and anywhere," says Justin Brookman, responsible for consumer privacy within the CDT (Center for Democracy and Technology) in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in one, and pessimism, in the other?
The biometrics will be based on new technologies that will provide new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its constraints.
"For example, some people working concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," says Philippe Robin, technical director of the identity domain at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection as well as the verification of the venous network and the contour of the hand require a voluntary and precise gesture of people.
It is both a security - it is not possible to capture these data to their unconsciousness - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore take time.
As a result, research has been conducted for twenty years on other approaches, such as the recognition of face or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to the increased accuracy of sensors and the ability to calculate computers required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The precision of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the last five years, explains Cyrille Bataller, Director of Accenture R & D Laboratorys in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic frontier positions using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a face or iris in motion.
"Today we are conducting research on voice recognition or how to walk through sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," says Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Intel Labs Security Research.
A unique and infalsible marker, DNA also raises hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be considered the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers the judicial police a suitcase costing EUR 90,000 to analyze DNA samples on the scene of a crime and within an hour.
The uses of biometrics are divided into two groups: identification (recognition of one person among others) and authentication (sure that the person is the person it claims to be).
To date, the identification concerned the issue of identity documents: biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) must be confronted with the information that the State possesses on all citizens already listed.
This makes it possible to make sure that one person does not try to abuse the identity of someone else.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus proposes the recognition of VIP at the entrance of a hotel or shop.
"We recover the images of the surveillance cameras and compare them with the photos of the celebrities that circulate freely on the Internet," Dany Nassif, charged, at NEC France, with commercial development for biometric identification solutions.
Other use: take a quidam in photo that makes the queue in a store, follow his progression thanks to facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
The authentication initially concerned physical access (frontiers, protected premises, cantines, etc.) or logical (opening of a computer).
It has been added, more recently, to the presence control.
"One biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the boyfriend who pointes for another," explains Cyrille Bataller, of Accenture.
But more and more authentication will also apply to transactions, especially those made from Internet-connected devices.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from some distributors by introducing its card and placing its hand on a biometric player: this gesture replaces the hit of the secret code.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with banks and large distribution teachers: at the time of paying in store with its bank card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader who scans the veins.
The experiment is scheduled to last for six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Tracks to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometrics attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can make time.
"If, thanks to biometrics, a client stays in cash 30 seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large surface.
The second is to offer customized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
Finally, rest assured by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; people's identities are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure housing, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin, from Thales.
But, lack of thorough studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convincing users.
Privacy specialists continue to be concerned.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, make me fear the worst: generalized surveillance," predicted Andrew Patrick, Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
