Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's queue are linked to his mood.
Previous studies had shown that happy dogs were moving more their queue to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs moved it more to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist from the University of Trent, said: "Everyone knows that in man, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in the stimulation of positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was going on with other species.
He added that, as in man, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to dissatisfaction of other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies of other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of animals and analysed their behaviour.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their queue sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We presented to dogs of movies with other dogs – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other factor of confusion – and we could trade the movement of the queue and present it as more left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expressing the queue to the right (from the dog's point of view that's the queue), they stayed perfectly relaxed.
But when they noticed a dive mainly to the left (only once from the dog's point of view that stitches the dick), their heart rate accelerated and they seemed anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think the dogs were deliberately communicating with each other thanks to these movements.
He thinks that dogs know from experience the movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their queue to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that the results could allow owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animals.
The Canin Behaviour Expert John Bradshaw, a professor invited to the Bristol University Veterinary School, stated that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canin species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study carried out by the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "The dogs were more easily going to a robot dog when his queue turned to the left rather than to the right, rather than becoming anxious – the opposite of what is in the Italian study."
He indicated that differences could arise from the fact that dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider the animals of movies or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to true dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, recorded in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are not an exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviour can be recorded, it is probably not long before we understand why their queue sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
