A team of biologists led by the New York Wildlife Conservation Society identified a new species of dolphin in the north coast of Australia.
Thibaut Bouveroux, responsible for scientific mission at the Observatory for the Conservation and Study of Animals and Environmentx Marins (OCEAMM) returns to L'Express on this discovery and explains the long process of identifying new species.
Does the discovery of this new type of dolphin at work surprise you?
It's a good news, but I'm not surprised.
If in the past, species have been described and identified on a morphological, anatomic and geographical basis, today, the development of new tools such as genetics enables us to improve our knowledge of species classification science.
Moreover, it is not possible that such progress in genetics and molecular biology jeopardize the classification or belonging of a species to a genre, a family or even an order.
At the beginning of the 19th century, morphologists classified animals based on morphological differences between species.
Today, some of these classifications are challenged due to the progress of genetics.
Similarly, two very close morphological species were distinguished by genetics.
This is the case with the new species that has just been identified.
A dozen years ago, the scientific community recognized two species belonging to this subfamily: Pacific dolphins and Atlantic dolphins.
Recent analyses have made it possible to distinguish four species.
Why is this an important discovery as stated by the Wildlife Conservation Society?
From a conservation point of view, it is essential to know these genetic differences in order to protect the species and thus its genetic variability.
Although this population had been known for a long time by the researchers, they did not know that it was part of a new species, present only in this place.
Therefore, if a problem of mass mortality caused by a virus epidemic or accidental capture occurs in the region, we could deal with the eradication of a species rather than with the local disappearance of a population of a more widespread species on Earth.
This loss of genetic heritage would be much more problematic.
A species is considered to be threatened or being extinct based on the number of existing individuals on Earth, i.e. stocks, and the possibility of recovery from neighbouring stocks.
With regard to the species Sousa chinensis, the population of the new species discovered, its stock has automatically become weaker, making it more vulnerable.
Why is it rare to discover new species of marine mammals?
Marine mammals are located at the top of the food chain.
They live in homogeneous, open habitats in which there are many genetic exchanges between populations and individuals.
This gene brewing limits the creation of new species.
On the other hand, more closed ecosystems promote genetic isolation, which can eventually lead to the creation of new species.
We must know that the marine environment is the least known environment.
One prefers to send robots to Mars, rather than to know what lives in the Marian's pit, just 11 kilometres from the sea surface.
More money is spent in life research on other planets than in marine research, and it's time that this changes.
