There's a lot of patients.
People can die because they wait too long.
The situation has not changed much since Dr. Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants, according to the World Health Organization.
As a comparison, the United States ratio is 1 doctor for 413 inhabitants.
And even if they could see a doctor, many Cameroonians could not pay for the consultation.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty threshold, and nearly three quarters of the country's health spending are carried out in the private sector.
"The only problem they have is poverty," Dr. Bwelle explained.
And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy life.
After seeing his father and his fellow countrymen suffer, Dr. Bwelle was determined to try to change the course of things.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team performed over 700 surgical acts free of charge over the past year.
He became a doctor himself, working as a vascular surgeon at the central hospital of Yaoundé.
And he established a non-profit humanitarian association, ASCOVIME, who travels to rural areas during weekends to provide free health care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, with about 30 people, they go into vans after fixing medical equipment on the roof and crossing difficult terrains to go to the villages most in need of help.
Lucky doesn't always follow them.
They have often had to push the vehicles to cross rivers or muddy tracks.
