The next morning, the team begins to receive hundreds of patients.
"We receive 500 people at each visit," said Mr. Bwelle.
They sometimes live 60 km from the village, and they come on foot.
In this traveling hospital, various health care is provided.
Many people receive treatment against malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others can receive bowls, a pair of collected glasses or a free birth certificate – document necessary to go to school, but many poor families simply cannot afford to buy it.
In the evening, the team practiced simple surgical acts under local anaesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school, a mayor or a home; after the intervention, the patient rises and goes to the wake-up room to leave his or her place to the next person.
Thanks to the lighting of the generator group, the operating room and the sterilization of the equipment, Dr. Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's a breathtaking pace, but village musicians generally help the team to remain motivated.
"They hit drums all night to keep us awake so we can keep working," Bwelle explained.
On Sunday, the team returns to town, tired but proud of the work she has done.
The group, composed of Cameroonian doctors and medical students, performed 700 surgical acts free of charge over the past year, and he knows that their presence can make the difference for those they come to help.
A man explained that the free operation he had undergone to cure a hernia would allow him to work again.
"This will change my future and that of my family," said the man.
In addition to making this traveling hospital live and work as a surgeon at the hospital, Dr. Bwelle also works at private hospitals around Yaoundé at night.
It is this second job, he explains, which finances its association at 60%; the rest is covered by private donations.
"I don't know when he's sleeping," said Katie O'Malley, a second-year medical student from Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteer in Dr. Bwelle's group.
He is still in the hospital or is trying to find money for his association to be able to carry out these campaigns.
For medical students and nurses such as Katie O'Malley, who come from the United States and Europe to join Mr. Bwelle in his missions, this is an opportunity to learn in the field that they don't have at home.
"We have been able to participate in operations to help dig the blood or transfer the instruments to Dr. Bwelle," said Ms. O'Malley.
This is not something you have the opportunity to do in America when you are a doctor in second year.
Volunteer students generally pay their trip to Cameroon, and often arrive with collected medical equipment.
But once in Yaoundé, their pension, transport and education are taken care of by Dr. Bwelle.
"He's a hero, there's no doubt," said Katie O'Malley.
He gives his life for this association, and his desire to help the Cameroonian people is not close to extinction.
For Dr. Bwelle, the relatively constant workload is not a problem.
Helping others to live happy by keeping the promise he made to his father is something that brings him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this job," said Mr. Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I'm doing.
Make people laugh and relieve pain are the reasons why I do this.
